<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-linear-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear Functions</title>

  <p> Text of section. </p>

  <p>
    There are many ways to write the equation of a line. We'll focus on two: <term>Point-Slope Form</term> and <term>Slope-
    Intercept Form</term>.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-point-slope-form">
    <title>Point-Slope Form</title>

    <p>
      This form is good if you just want to write the equation of a line and don't mind if it's messy. Here are the steps
      for writing the equation of a line in point-slope form.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find one point on the line, <m>(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find the slope of the line, <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plug the point and slope into the equation
          <md>
            y-b = m(x-a)
          </md>
          In this equation, <m>a</m>,<m>b</m>, and <m>m</m> will be numbers that you plug in, and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
          will remain as variables.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <example><title>Equation in Point-Slope Form</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation for the given line. Write your answer in Point-Slope Form.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
          <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-line" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = 3*x-5
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-1,-6,5,5]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          If you use the point <m>(2,1)</m>, the answer is <m>y-1 = 3(x-2)</m>. Choosing a different point will result
          in an equivalent answer. No matter which point you choose, though, your slope will be 3.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              First we need to choose a point on the line. I will choose the point <m>(a,b)=(2,1)</m>, but you could use other
              points on the graph instead, like <m>(3,4)</m> or <m>(1,-2)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Using two points on the graph, we need to find the slope. I will use the points <m>(2,1)</m> and <m>(3,4)</m>.
              With these, I compute the slope.
              <md>
                m = \frac{1-4}{2-3} = \frac{-3}{-1} = 3
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Plugging this point and slope into the equation for Point-Slope Form, we get
              <md>
                y-1 = 3(x-2)
              </md>
              If you choose a different point in Step 1, it will result in a different but equivalent answer. For example,
              if you use the point <m>(3,4)</m>, your answer will be <md>y-4 = 3(x-3)</md>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
  </subsection>

</section>